              }
            ],
            "defaultServings": 6
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Prepare the night before",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Score the skin at 1 cm intervals if the butcher has not already done so. Cutting through the skin but not deep into the fat. Pat completely dry with kitchen paper.",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": []
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Rub the salt and crushed fennel seeds generously over the skin, pressing into the score cuts. Leave uncovered in the fridge overnight.",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": []
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Slow-roast and blast",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 160 degrees C fan. Scatter the onion, garlic, and thyme in the base of a deep roasting tin. Pour in the cider. Sit the pork belly on top, skin side up.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Roast uncovered for 2 hours 45 minutes. The fat will have rendered and the meat will be tender.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Raise the oven to 230 degrees C fan and roast for a further 20 to 25 minutes until the ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "crackling",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpdr2rmg0000vkv4eurv2hwe"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " is completely blistered and shattering.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Transfer to a board and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "rest",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpedfvv30001x4v4rzqb2aze"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " for 20 minutes. The crackling will continue to crisp as it rests.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Ensure the skin is bone-dry before it goes in the oven. If the crackling is still soft after the blast, transfer the pork to a tray, remove the crackling in a sheet, and grill it on high for 5 minutes watching carefully.",
                "cause": "The skin was not dry enough, or the high-heat blast was not long enough.",
                "symptom": "Crackling is chewy and soft rather than crisp"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Score the skin properly: the cuts need to reach through the skin layer. A Stanley blade works better than most kitchen knives.",
                "cause": "The scores were not cut deep enough to the skin, leaving thick uncut sections.",
                "symptom": "The crackling is dark in patches but raw-looking in others"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Always add liquid to the base of the tin. The steam helps keep the underside of the pork moist while the skin crisps above.",
                "cause": "The tin was too shallow with no liquid, or the oven temperature was too high.",
                "symptom": "The meat has dried out during the long cook"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Check at the 90-minute mark and add more cider or stock if the base is drying out.",
                "cause": "The liquid boiled away during the long cook.",
                "symptom": "The base of the tin has burnt"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "A rub of five-spice and garlic instead of fennel gives a Chinese-influenced version. For a simpler finish, omit the fennel and use just salt. The cooking liquid in the base makes an excellent gravy: strain it, skim the fat. And reduce by half on the hob.",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Roast pork belly became popular in British restaurants in the 1990s and 2000s as chefs discovered what Asian and Italian cooks had always known: that the belly is a better roasting cut than the loin. It produces more flavour, more fat, and more satisfying crackling than any other pork joint.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "servings": 6,
    "yieldDescription": null,
    "difficulty": "BEGINNER"
  },
